Pierce the potatoes several times with a fork to allow the steam to escape. Then, coat the potatoes in a light coat of olive oil. The oil will not adhere to the potato as well if they are wet or damp. Sprinkle the potatoes with salt and pepper. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/b/b9/Make-a-Baked-Potato-Skin-Crispy-Step-2Bullet2.jpg/v4-459px-Make-a-Baked-Potato-Skin-Crispy-Step-2Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/b/b9/Make-a-Baked-Potato-Skin-Crispy-Step-2Bullet2.jpg/v4-759px-Make-a-Baked-Potato-Skin-Crispy-Step-2Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":506.31868131868134,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
